<p>September arrives and the marinas start to thin out. The last of the summer visitors have departed, the evening light comes earlier, and the conversation at the yacht club shifts from passage planning to winterisation. Whether you lift out for the winter or keep your boat afloat, the decisions you make in October and November have a direct impact on how ready your vessel is when April rolls around.</p>

<p>This guide covers the hull care aspects of winter preparation — with specific notes for each of our three South Devon marinas.</p>

<h2>If You're Lifting Out</h2>

<p>The haul-out itself is the obvious starting point. Book early — Upham's Yard in Brixham, Noss-on-Dart, and the various Torquay yard facilities all fill up quickly from September onwards. If you wait until November, you may find your preferred dates are gone.</p>

<p>Once your boat is out of the water, resist the urge to immediately pressure wash the hull. If you're planning to get a professional assessment of your antifouling condition — and we'd recommend it — the fouling pattern on your hull as it comes out of the water tells a story. Where is the fouling heaviest? Where has the antifouling held up well? Are there areas where primer is showing through? This information guides your repaint decisions far better than a freshly blasted hull can.</p>

<p>If you've had a robotic hull clean earlier in the season, your hull will come out significantly cleaner than if you haven't. Many of our clients who clean quarterly find that their autumn haul-out requires only light washing rather than heavy scrubbing — which saves yard time and preserves more of the existing antifouling for next season.</p>

<h2>If You're Staying Afloat</h2>

<p>Not everyone lifts out for winter. In Dartmouth, where the River Dart provides sheltered year-round mooring, many boat owners keep their vessels in the water twelve months a year. Some Torquay and Brixham berth holders do the same, particularly those with larger vessels where the lift-out cost is substantial.</p>

<p>For boats staying afloat, winter hull care takes on a different character. Biological fouling growth slows dramatically as water temperatures drop below 8°C — but it doesn't stop entirely. More importantly, silt deposition continues regardless of temperature. In Dartmouth, river sediment settles on hulls throughout winter, creating a compacted layer that becomes increasingly difficult to remove as it ages.</p>

<p>Our recommendation for boats staying afloat over winter:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Late October/November clean:</strong> Remove the season's accumulated fouling before winter. This prevents autumn growth from hardening through the cold months into tough, well-bonded fouling that's expensive to remove in spring.</li>
  <li><strong>Mid-winter inspection (January/February):</strong> A visual inspection during the quietest fouling period gives you the clearest possible view of your antifouling condition. With minimal biological growth obscuring the surface, any paint degradation, thinning, or damage is most visible now.</li>
  <li><strong>Early spring clean (March):</strong> As temperatures start rising and biological activity accelerates, a pre-season clean gives you a fresh baseline. Spring fouling settles onto a clean hull rather than onto winter's accumulated silt layer, making your antifouling more effective from day one of the new season.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Location-Specific Winter Notes</h2>

<p><strong>Brixham:</strong> The harbour's enclosed nature provides good winter shelter, and the tidal access constraints are actually less problematic during winter because there's less competition for the tidal windows. If you're staying afloat, the fishing fleet's winter operations continue to add nutrients to the harbour water, meaning even winter fouling can be more noticeable here than at Torquay. Consider a January clean if you see green waterline build-up.</p>

<p><strong>Torquay:</strong> The lock gate provides full protection from winter weather, and the marina's facilities remain operational year-round. The marina typically schedules pontoon maintenance during the quieter winter months, so check with the marina office about any access disruptions to your berth. The English Riviera's milder winter temperatures mean biological activity persists later into autumn and starts earlier in spring than you might expect — don't assume December is too early for this year's final clean.</p>

<p><strong>Dartmouth:</strong> The River Dart sees increased freshwater flow during winter rainfall, which drops salinity and can affect marine fouling organisms. However, this same rainfall carries Dartmoor sediment into the estuary, increasing silt deposition on hulls. Winter on the Dart is predominantly a silt management challenge rather than a biological fouling challenge. Our winter clean for Dartmouth boats focuses on removing compacted river sediment before it bonds permanently to the antifouling surface.</p>

<h2>The Spring Advantage of Winter Care</h2>

<p>Boat owners who invest in winter hull maintenance consistently report a better start to the following season. Their antifouling is in better condition because it hasn't been buried under months of compacted fouling. Their hull is smoother, meaning better performance from the first spring outing. And they've identified any issues — paint failure, surface damage, intake blockages — during the quiet season when fixing them is cheaper and easier than during the busy spring rush.</p>

<p>The worst time to discover your antifouling needs replacing is in April, when every boatyard in South Devon has a three-week queue for the paint shed. The best time to discover it is in January, when you can book at your leisure and have everything sorted well before launch day.</p>

